    title: 'Formations',
    subtitle: '阵法 — Zhèn Fǎ',
    body: `Formations are the third of the Four Great Arts — the art of arranging Qi, intent, and material into patterns that bend reality within their bounds. A formation is part mathematics, part calligraphy, part spell: the array master inscribes lines and nodes, anchors them with formation flags or spirit stones, and the resulting field does what the master designed.

Formations gather Qi, trap enemies, defend a sect mountain, conceal a ruin, summon illusions, or amplify cultivation. They scale endlessly: a small trap-array can be laid by a Foundation cultivator in minutes; a sect-protecting grand array can take generations of masters to complete and may outlast the sect itself.

Formation Masters are prized by every faction, for a single master can multiply a sect's defensive strength many times over. The deepest formation Dao treats the world itself as the array: mountains as nodes, rivers as lines, the heaven as the master. Some say the oldest formations are not made but found — the bones of the world, inscribed by hands no living being remembers.`,
    tags: ['formations', 'four-great-arts', 'array-master', 'law'],
